39 || 0 || 9 || 127 || 2,447 || 10 || 97\n|- \n| 20 Apr || 0 || 239 || 1 || 10 || 44 || 2,491 || 15 || 112\n|- \n| 21 Apr || 2 || 241 || 0 || 10 || 70 || 2,561 || 11 || 123\n|- \n| 22 Apr || 2 || 243 || 0 || 10 || 74 || 2,635 || 11 || 134\n|- \n| 23 Apr || 2 || 245 || 0 || 10 || 92 || 2,727 || 5 || 139\n|- style=\"text-align:right;\"\n! Total\n! style='background: #DCDCDC;' |\n! 245\n! style='background: #DCDCDC;' |\n! 10\n! style='background: #DCDCDC;' |\n! 2,727\n! style='background: #DCDCDC;' |\n! 139\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory]]\n*[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Jersey]]\n*[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Isle of Man]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:Guernsey]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Guernsey]]\n[[Category:2020 in Guernsey|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Guernsey]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Crown dependencies|Guernsey]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Guernsey]]\n", "name_user": "Formulaonewiki", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCase grouping:restore type", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Guernsey"}
{"title_page": "Chris Wakelin", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox snooker player\n| name          = Chris Wakelin\n| image         = Chris Wakelin PHC 2016-1.jpg\n| caption       = Paul Hunter Classic 2016\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1992|3|16}}\n| birth_place   = [[Rugby, Warwickshire|Rugby]], [[England]]\n| Sport country = {{ENG}}\n| Nickname      = \n| Professional  = 2013\u2013\n| High ranking  = 44 <small>(September 2018)</small>\n| Prize money   = [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]228,665\n| High break    = '''144''': <br> <small>2018 Paul Hunter Classic</small>\n| Century break = 52\n| Best finish   = ''Quarter-final'' <small>([[2015 Indian Open]], [[2016 English Open (snooker)|2016 English Open]], [[2018 Riga Masters]])</small>\n| Ranking wins  = \n| Minor wins    =\n| World champ   = \n}}\n\n'''Chris Wakelin''' (born 16 March 1992)<ref name=\"2013/14\" /> is an English professional [[snooker]] player from [[Rugby, Warwickshire]]. He practices frequently with [[Kyren Wilson]], [[David Gilbert (snooker player)|David Gilbert]] and [[Mark Selby]] at the Atack Club in [[Nuneaton]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Wakelin Q&A|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~4121276,00.html|publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]]|accessdate=9 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early career===\nWakelin started playing snooker aged 8, when his parents Mark and Angie bought him his first mini snooker table, and by the time he was 11 he was successfully playing in the local league.<ref name=\"ra\">{{cite web|title=Chris has staked it all on a pot of gold |url=http://www.rugbyadvertiser.co.uk/sport/chris-has-staked-it-all-on-a-pot-of-gold-1-5038412|publisher=Rugby Advertiser|accessdate=31 July 2013|date=28 April 2013}}</ref> However his career nearly came to a halt at the age of 17 when he had to start working full-time as [[ASDA]] delivery driver to support himself financially, and only played snooker as a hobby. In 2012 Wakelin decided to give the game another go but soon had to face more difficulties as family issues resulted in a severe depression: \"I could line up but I just couldn\u2019t pot. I thought I would never play again. But thankfully with the help of my friends I managed to turn it around.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Evans|first=Gregg|title=Chris takes his cue from bizarre accident|url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/other-sport/big-break-set-chris-wakelin-4324852|publisher=[[Birmingham Mail]]|accessdate=31 July 2013|date=16 June 2013}}</ref> Since then Wakelin reached the semi-finals of the 2013 English Amateur Championship, before making it through to the England's Under 21 final (where he would later beat [[Hammad Miah]]).<ref name=\"ra\" /><ref name=\"ro\">{{cite web|last=Arrowsmith|first=Jamie|title=Wakelin set to star on the baize|url=http://www.therugbyobserver.co.uk/2013/06/23/sport-Wakelin-set-to-star-on-the-baize-74739.html|publisher=[[Rugby Observer]]|accessdate=31 July 2013|date=19 June 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219190023/http://www.therugbyobserver.co.uk/2013/06/23/sport-Wakelin-set-to-star-on-the-baize-74739.html|archivedate=19 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThese results encouraged him to enter [[World Snooker Tour#Q School|Q School]] in May. After having made it to the final round of the first event, he again reached the final round at the Event 3. There he faced former professional [[Adam Wicheard]], who led 2\u20130 before Wakelin hit back to lead 3\u20132. Then, in the sixth frame when Wakelin was already 23\u20130 up, Wicheard accidentally snapped his cue when leaning on it, and had to concede the match.<ref name=\"ro\" /> As a result, Wakelin won a tour card for the [[2013\u201314 snooker season|2013\u201314]] and [[2014\u201315 snooker season|2014\u201315]] seasons.\n\n===2013/2014 season===\nWakelin had a tough debut season as a professional as he lost his opening match in all the ranking tournaments aside from the [[2013 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]], where he defeated 22nd seed [[Ryan Day (snooker player)|Ryan Day]] 6\u20135 before losing by the same scoreline to [[Jamie Burnett]] in the subsequent round.<ref name=\"2013/14\">{{cite web|title=Chris Wakelin 2013/2014|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?season=2013&player=1044|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=10 April 2014}}</ref> He had better results in the minor-ranking [[Players Tour Championship 2013/2014|European Tour]] events, reaching the last 32 of the [[European Tour 2013/2014 \u2013 Event 2|Rotterdam Open]] before going all the way to the quarter-finals of the [[European Tour 2013/2014 \u2013 Event 6|Kay Suzanne Memorial Cup]], where he lost 4\u20132 to [[Judd Trump]].<ref name=\"2013/14\"/> Wakelin's season ended when he was edged out 10\u20139 by [[Paul Davison]] in the first round of [[2014 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] qualifying, with him ranked world number 106 after his first year on tour.<ref>{{cite web|title=Steadman Sets Up Davis Meeting|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3756983,00.html|publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]]|accessdate=10 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/71/c1/0,,13165~180593,00.pdf |title=World Snooker Rankings After the 2014 World Championship |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |accessdate=8 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140508030740/http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/71/c1/0%2C%2C13165~180593%2C00.pdf |archivedate=8 May 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===2014/2015 season===\nWakelin's second season on the tour was a vast improvement on his first. He beat [[Tom Ford (snooker player)|Tom Ford]] 5\u20132 to qualify for the [[2014 Wuxi Classic]] and in his first appearance in a ranking event outside of the UK he overcame Joe O'Connor 5\u20132, before losing 5\u20132 to [[Shaun Murphy (snooker player)|Shaun Murphy]].<ref name=\"2014/15\">{{cite web|title=Chris Wakelin 2014/2015|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?season=2014&player=1044|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> At the minor-ranking [[European Tour 2014/2015 \u2013 Event 4|Ruhr Open]], Wakelin overcame [[Matthew Stevens]] 4\u20131 and then fought back from 3\u20130 and needing two snookers in the deciding frame to beat [[Thepchaiya Un-Nooh]] 4\u20133. A 4\u20132 win over [[Fergal O'Brien]] saw him reach the quarter-finals where he lost 4\u20131 to [[Judd Trump]].<ref name=\"2014/15\"/> At the [[2015 Indian Open|Indian Open]], Wakelin beat Rhys Clark 4\u20132, [[Andrew Pagett]] 4\u20131 and [[Nigel Bond]] 4\u20131 to play in the quarter-finals of a ranking event for the first time.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/wakelin-keeps-run-going/ | title=Wakelin Keeps Run Going | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> He was 2\u20131 ahead of [[Michael White (snooker player)|Michael White]], but would lose 4\u20132.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/white-makes-semi-breakthrough/ | title=White Makes Semi Breakthrough | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nWakelin's performances in the [[Players Tour Championship 2014/2015|European Tour]] events this season saw him finish a lofty 22nd on the [[Players Tour Championship 2014/2015#European Tour|Order of Merit]] to earn a new two-year tour card.<ref>{{cite web|title=European Order of Merit 2014/2015|url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?template=10&season=2014|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> It also gave him entry into the [[Players Tour Championship 2014/2015 \u2013 Finals|Grand Final]] where he whitewashed [[Robert Milkins]] 4\u20130, before [[Matthew Selt]] ousted Wakelin 4\u20132 in the second round.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/williams-fight-back-floors-selby/ | title=Williams Fight Back Floors Selby | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2015/2016 season===\nWakelin saw off Alex Taubman 5\u20131, [[Craig Steadman]] 5\u20130 and [[Liam Highfield]] 5\u20132 to reach the final qualifying round of the [[2015 Australian Goldfields Open|Australian Goldfields Open]], but lost 5\u20133 to [[Jamie Jones (snooker player)|Jamie Jones]].<ref name=\"2015/16\">{{cite web | url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=1044&season=2015 | title=Chris Wakelin 2015/2016 | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref> A 6\u20134 victory over [[Peter Lines]] saw him qualify for the [[2015 International Championship|International Championship]], where he lost 6\u20134 to [[Barry Hawkins]] having led 3\u20131.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/34633368 | title=Champion Ricky Walden beaten by Tian Pengfei in China | publisher=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref> Wakelin beat [[Matthew Stevens]] 6\u20135 on the final black in the first round of the [[2015 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]] and apologised to his opponent for an exuberant celebration at the end in a win he described as one of his best.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/34932083 | title=UK Championship 2015: Chris Wakelin in pieces at black-ball win | publisher=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref> He was defeated 6\u20132 by [[Michael Holt (snooker player)|Michael Holt]] in the second round. Wakelin qualified for the [[2016 China Open (snooker)|China Open]] by eliminating [[Kurt Maflin]] 5\u20133 and was edged out 5\u20134 by [[Matthew Selt]] in the first round.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nuneaton-news.co.uk/Wakelin-hopes-make-Crucible-cut/story-29056230-detail/story.html | title=Snooker: Wakelin hopes to make the Crucible cut | publisher=[[Nuneaton News]] | accessdate=25 April 2016}}</ref> After beating world number 25 and former practice partner [[Ben Woollaston]] 10\u20139, Wakelin looked set to reach the final qualifying round for the [[2016 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] after leading [[Anthony Hamilton (snooker player)|Anthony Hamilton]] 4\u20130 and 9\u20136, but went on to lose 10\u20139.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nuneaton-news.co.uk/Snooker-World-Championship-2016-Wakelin-suffers/story-29089881-detail/story.html | title=Snooker World Championship 2016: Wakelin suffers comeback defeat | publisher=[[Nuneaton News]] | accessdate=25 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2016/2017 season===\nWins over [[Allan Taylor (snooker player)|Allan Taylor]] and [[Anthony McGill (snooker player)|Anthony McGill]] saw Wakelin set up a third round encounter with [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] in the third round of the [[2016 English Open (snooker)|English Open]]. Wakelin recovered from 2\u20130 down to triumph 4\u20133 in a performance that included a century and two other breaks above 50.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.eurosport.co.uk/snooker/english-open/2016-2017/ronnie-o-sullivan-defeated-by-chris-wakelin-at-the-english-open_sto5908766/story.shtml| title=Ronnie O'Sullivan defeated by Chris Wakelin at the English Open, Judd Trump beats Martin Gould| publisher=[[Eurosport]]| accessdate=12 April 2017}}</ref> He then edged past [[Xiao Guodong]] 4\u20133 after trailing 3\u20131 to play in the quarter-finals, where he lost 5\u20130 to [[Stuart Bingham]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://livescores.worldsnookerdata.com/Matches/Result/13910/443022|title=Xiao Guodong 3\u20134 Chris Wakelin|publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]]|accessdate=12 April 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170402234903/http://livescores.worldsnookerdata.com/Matches/Result/13910/443022|archivedate=2 April 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://rugbyobserver.co.uk/sport/fairytale-run-snookers-new-english-open-ends-chris-wakelin-heavy-defeat-stuart-bingham/|title=Fairytale run in snooker's new English Open ends for Chris Wakelin after heavy defeat to Stuart Bingham|publisher=Rugby and Lutterworth Observer|accessdate=12 April 2017}}</ref> Wakelin was defeated 6\u20134 by [[Peter Lines]] in the second round of the [[2016 UK Championship|UK Championship]] and 4\u20130 by [[Anthony Hamilton (snooker player)|Anthony Hamilton]] in the third round of the [[2016 Scottish Open (snooker)|Scottish Open]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=1044|title=Chris Wakelin 2016/2017|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=12 April 2017}}</ref> Wakelin ended a season inside the top 64 for the first time as he was the world number 63.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rankings 2016/2017|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?season=2016&template=31|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=7 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Performance and rankings timeline==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:85%;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#efefef\"\n! '''Tournament'''\n! [[2012\u201313 snooker season|2012/<br/>13]]\n! [[2013\u201314 snooker season|2013/<br/>14]]\n! [[2014\u201315 snooker season|2014/<br/>15]]\n! [[2015\u201316 snooker season|2015/<br/>16]]\n! [[2016\u201317 snooker season|2016/<br/>17]]\n! [[2017\u201318 snooker season|2017/<br/>18]]\n! [[2018\u201319 snooker season|2018/<br/>19]]\n! [[2019\u201320 snooker season|2019/<br/>20]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[Snooker world rankings|Ranking]]<ref name=\"Ranking history\">{{cite web|title=Ranking History|url=http://www.snooker.org/rnk/history.asp|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref><ref group=\"nb\">It shows the ranking at the beginning of the season.</ref> \n| align=\"center\" |<ref group=\"nb\">He was an amateur.</ref> \n| align=\"center\" |<ref group=\"nb\" name=\"UR\">New players on the Main Tour don't have a ranking.</ref>\n| align=\"center\" |{{nowrap|[[Snooker world rankings 2014/2015|106]]}}\n| align=\"center\" |<ref group=\"nb\" name=\"ET\">Players qualified through European Tour Order of Merit started the season without prize money ranking points.</ref>\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 2016/2017|83]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 2017/2018|63]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 2018/2019|48]]\n| align=\"center\" |[[Snooker world rankings 2019/2020|48]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"10\" | '''Ranking tournaments'''\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"| [[Riga Masters (snooker)|Riga Masters]]<ref group=\"nb\">The event was called the Riga Open (2014/2015\u20132015/2016)</ref>\n|align=\"center\" colspan=\"2\" style=\"color:#cccccc;\"| Not Held\n|colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; color:#ccc;\"| MR\n|style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2016 Riga Masters|1R]]\n|align=\"center\" style=\"color:#cccccc;\"|LQ\n|style=\"text-align:center; background:#ffebcd;\"|[[2018 Riga Masters|QF]]\n|align=\"center\" style=\"color:#cccccc;\"|LQ\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | {{nowrap|[[International Championship]]}} \n|align=\"center\" style=\"color:#cccccc;\"|A\n|align=\"center\" style=\"color:#cccccc;\"|LQ\n|align=\"center\" style=\"color:#cccccc;\"|LQ\n|align=\"center\" style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2015 International Championship|1R]]\n|align=\"center\" style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2016 International Championship|1R]]\n|align=\"center\" style=\"color:#cccccc;\"|LQ\n|style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2018 International Championship (snooker)|1R]]\n|style=\"text-align:center; background:#afeeee;\"|[[2019 International Championship (snooker)|1R]]\n|-\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"| [[China Championship (snooker)|China Championship]]\n|align=\"center\" colspan=\"4\" style=\"color:#cccccc;\"| Tournament Not Held\n|align=\"center\" style=\"color:#cccccc;\"|NR\n|align=\"